    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>The <strong>primary category in Google Business Profile (GBP)</strong> is the main classification that tells Google what type of business you operate. It is the strongest relevance signal for local pack rankings — a Sterling Sky study found that <strong>changing the primary category alone caused ranking shifts in 84% of tested cases</strong>. Google offers over 4,000 predefined categories that cannot be customised or combined.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Available categories</div>
            <div class="tms-value">4,000+</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">84% of cases</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local businesses get their GBP category wrong in one of two ways: they choose too broad a category ("Lawyer" instead of "Personal Injury Attorney") or they pad their listing with irrelevant secondary categories that dilute the primary relevance signal. Getting the primary category right is the highest-leverage, zero-cost change in local SEO.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the primary category in Google Business Profile?</h2>
        <p>When you create or edit a Google Business Profile, the first category you set is the primary category. It appears below your business name in Google Maps search results and Google's local pack, and it tells both users and Google's algorithm what your business fundamentally does.</p>
        <p>Key characteristics of the primary category:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>It is Google's predefined list only.</strong> You cannot create custom categories. If your business doesn't fit an existing category, choose the most specific accurate option.</li>
          <li><strong>It cannot combine multiple categories.</strong> You must choose one primary category. Additional categories (up to 9 more) serve secondary purposes.</li>
          <li><strong>It appears publicly in Maps.</strong> Users can see your primary category in search results and on your GBP listing page.</li>
          <li><strong>It determines available GBP attributes.</strong> Your primary category unlocks category-specific features: menus for restaurants, booking for healthcare providers, product showcases for retailers.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Sterling Sky Local Ranking Factor Study</div>
          <p>In controlled tests, <strong>changing the primary GBP category alone caused ranking changes in 84% of cases</strong>. No other single GBP optimisation — not review count, not photo updates, not description text — produced ranking changes in more cases. Category is the foundation.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why the primary category matters for local pack rankings</h2>
        <p>Google's local algorithm uses three primary signals to determine which businesses appear in the local pack: relevance, distance, and prominence. The primary category is Google's clearest input for relevance.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Relevance signal strength.</strong> When someone searches "personal injury attorney near me," Google's first filter is: which GBP listings have a category matching this intent? A law firm using "Lawyer" as its primary category will be outranked by a competitor using "Personal Injury Attorney" for personal injury queries — even if the first firm has more reviews and a higher domain authority website.</li>
          <li><strong>Attribute availability.</strong> The right category unlocks relevant attributes that increase conversion: "Women-led," "LGBTQ+ friendly," "Wheelchair accessible," or service-specific attributes like "free estimates" for contractors. Missing attributes because of a wrong category means missed conversion signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Review topic highlighting.</strong> Google's AI categorises review topics based on your primary category. A restaurant will have "food quality," "service," and "ambiance" highlighted. A law firm will have "professionalism" and "outcome" highlighted. The wrong category produces irrelevant highlights that confuse prospective clients.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitor comparison.</strong> When your listing appears alongside competitors in the local pack, Google uses category data to determine if businesses are comparable. Matching your competitors' most specific category ensures you're in the comparison set for the queries that matter.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to choose the right primary category</h2>
        <p>The selection process has four steps:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Search your target keyword in Google Maps.</strong> Type the query your best customers use to find businesses like yours. Look at the top 3-5 results in the local pack. Note the category label below each business name — that's their primary category.</li>
          <li><strong>Use a GBP category explorer tool.</strong> Tools like GMB Everywhere (Chrome extension), Pleper, or BrightLocal's GBP audit show category distributions across top-ranked competitors without clicking through each listing. Find the most common category among the top-ranked businesses for your primary queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Choose specificity over breadth.</strong> "Personal Injury Attorney" outperforms "Lawyer" for personal injury searches. "Italian Restaurant" outperforms "Restaurant" for Italian food searches. Always choose the most specific category that accurately describes your core business.</li>
          <li><strong>Validate with a test period.</strong> After changing your primary category, monitor your local pack position for your 3-5 most important queries over 2-4 weeks. Use a local rank tracker to measure position shifts.</li>
        </ol>

