            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real primary category examples that changed rankings</h2>

        <h3>1. Personal injury law firm — 40% visibility increase</h3>
        <p>A law firm using "Lawyer" as their primary GBP category switched to "Personal Injury Attorney" after a competitor audit showed all top-3 local pack results used the more specific category. Within 3 weeks, local pack visibility for "personal injury attorney [city]" queries increased by 40%. New monthly leads from Maps increased from 8 to 14.</p>

        <h3>2. Yoga studio outranking competitors</h3>
        <p>A fitness studio using "Gym" as their primary category was outranked on yoga queries by competitors using "Yoga Studio." After switching to "Yoga Studio" as primary and adding "Gym" and "Fitness Center" as secondary categories, the studio moved from position 6 to position 2 in local pack results for "yoga classes near me" over six weeks.</p>

        <h3>3. HVAC contractor — winning seasonal searches</h3>
        <p>An HVAC company using "HVAC Contractor" as primary added "Air Conditioning Contractor" as a secondary category before the summer season. Searches for "AC repair near me" and "air conditioning installation" increased by 35% in the first summer month post-change. The secondary category captured intent the primary category alone wouldn't reach.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Primary category vs business description — which drives rankings more?</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Primary category (higher impact)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Direct ranking signal — Google's first filter for relevance</li>
              <li>Determines local pack eligibility for service queries</li>
              <li>Unlocks category-specific features and attributes</li>
              <li>Affects which review topics Google highlights</li>
              <li>Visible to users in search results</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Business description (lower ranking impact)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Provides context but not a direct ranking signal</li>
              <li>Keywords in description have minimal local rank effect</li>
              <li>Visible on GBP listing page (conversion role)</li>
              <li>750 character limit</li>
              <li>Useful for conversion, not for ranking</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for GBP primary category selection</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Audit top local competitors before choosing.</strong> Never guess your category. Search your target queries in Maps, identify the categories of the top 3-5 ranked businesses, and align with the most specific category that accurately describes your services.</li>
          <li><strong>Choose based on revenue priority, not business breadth.</strong> If you're a law firm doing 80% personal injury but some family law, set "Personal Injury Attorney" as primary. The primary category should reflect your core revenue stream, not every service you offer.</li>
          <li><strong>Use secondary categories for service expansion.</strong> Add secondary categories that genuinely reflect services you provide and want to rank for. Don't pad — Google's quality algorithms detect irrelevant category stacking.</li>
          <li><strong>Check category changes 3-7 days after updating.</strong> GBP category changes take 3-7 days to propagate across Maps. Don't evaluate ranking impact in the first week.</li>
          <li><strong>Track local pack rankings before and after changes.</strong> Use a tool like BrightLocal, Local Falcon, or GeoRanker to measure position shifts at the keyword and location level. Category changes that help one query set sometimes hurt another.</li>
          <li><strong>Revisit category selection annually.</strong> Google adds new categories regularly. A category that didn't exist 18 months ago may now perfectly describe your business. Check for new additions using the GBP dashboard's category search field.</li>
          <li><strong>Align your website with your primary category.</strong> If your primary category is "Personal Injury Attorney," your website's H1, title tags, and service pages should reinforce that focus. Category signals and website signals that contradict each other reduce overall ranking strength.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — using a category that describes who you serve, not what you do</div>
          <p>Some businesses choose categories based on their target customer rather than their service type. A B2B accountant might choose "Business Consultant" because they serve businesses — but the right category is "Accountant" or "Certified Public Accountant (CPA)." Google's categories describe what you do, not who your customer is. Choosing based on customer type instead of service type will suppress visibility for the queries that actually drive revenue.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common primary category mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Choosing too broad a category</strong> — "Contractor" instead of "Roofing Contractor" means you're competing in a larger pool for queries that have a more specific match available.</li>
          <li><strong>Setting a secondary service as primary</strong> — if 80% of your revenue is landscaping and 20% is snow removal, "Landscaping Service" should be primary even if snow removal is higher margin.</li>
          <li><strong>Adding irrelevant secondary categories to appear for more queries</strong> — a dentist adding "Spa" as a category hoping to capture wellness searches. Google's quality systems detect this and may reduce overall listing trust.</li>
          <li><strong>Forgetting to update the category when expanding services</strong> — adding a new service line without reflecting it in secondary categories leaves ranking opportunity on the table.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring category changes after a GBP suspension resolution</strong> — Google sometimes resets categories during suspension reviews. Check your categories after any GBP suspension resolves.</li>
        </ul>

